{"title":"Data Augmentation for Graph Neural Networks","domain":"IR_REC","seeds":[{"problem":"Graph data augmentation for semi-supervised node classification is challenging: naive/random edge edits can degrade performance, and we need a label-free way to denoise observed graphs by promoting intra-class connectivity and suppressing inter-class edges.","method":"GAUG-M uses a neural edge predictor (Graph Auto-Encoder, GAE) to estimate edge probabilities over all node pairs, then deterministically modifies the graph by adding the top i|E| non-edges and removing the bottom j|E| existing edges by predicted probability. The resulting modified graph G_m replaces the original graph for both training and inference, effectively denoising structure by approximating class-homophily. Experiments show learned additions/removals increase intra-class edges and improve node classification vs. random edits."},{"problem":"In dynamic or latency-constrained settings, the graph cannot be modified at inference time, so we need augmentation that improves generalization while training on plausible structural variants but testing on the original graph.","method":"GAUG-O builds an end-to-end, stochastic augmentation pipeline: a GAE predicts edge probabilities M, which are interpolated with the original adjacency A via a mixing coefficient α to form P; per iteration, a sparse variant adjacency A' is sampled using a relaxed Bernoulli (Gumbel-Softmax) with a straight-through estimator, exposing the node classifier to new graph variants each step. Training optimizes a joint loss combining node-classification (L_nc) and edge-prediction reconstruction (β·L_ep) to prevent drift from A. At inference, the GNN operates on the original graph, yielding improved performance via learned, differentiable graph augmentation."}]}
